{
  "text": "Fourth, we expected that men would perform worse on the go/no-go task when presented with sexual stimuli than would women, since, compared to women, men demonstrate stronger approach tendencies to sexual stimuli [CITATION_1] and are shown to be more sexually excitable and less sexually inhibited [CITATION_2] . Finally, we expected that participants would perform better after the contingency reversal, which would demonstrate learning over the course of the task. However, we expected that high levels of impulsivity and sexual excitation, and low sexual inhibition and intellectual abilities, would be linked to worse performance on the task following the reversal.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "13336463",
    "[CITATION_2]": "17729891"
